Understanding CIDR - IPv4 ( classless inter domain routing ) octets 

→  Base IP address : starting point of the range [ 0-255 ] . [ 0-255 ] . [ 0-255 ] . [ 0-255 ]  max 32

→ Subnet mask : defines how many bits change in the IP 
- /24 = 24 bits are for the network portion  & remaining 8 bits ‎ = 1 bytehost addresses within the network 
- /32 = unique address and pin pointing a single ip address (no room for host range )

To find out IP range 
- 192.168.0.0 - 192.168.0.255 ( count the .0 as one IP so it is 256)
- /24 - 32 = 8  
- So 2 * 8  = 256 Ip addresses  = your CIDR range **

- /0 = all IP addresses 


There’s only 4 octaves available [0-255]

192.168.0.0/16 = so 16 bits are for the network and the rest for host range 
16-32 = 16 
So 2 * 16 =65,536 - ip’s 
192.168.255.255


IANA - internet assigned numbers authority established blocks of IPv4 address that can be used by private ( LAN ) and Public ( Internet ) addresses 

Private can only allow certain values : These three ranges, they're usually considered private IPs with the exception of 127.0.0.1

10.0.0.0 - 10.255.255.255 = 10.0.0.0/8 - in big networks 

172.16.0.0 - 172.31.255.255 = 172.16.0.0/12 - AWS default VPC in that range 

192.168.0.0 - 192.168.255.255 = 192.168.0.0/16 - home networks 

[ All the rest of the IP addresses on the internet are public ]


Default Virtual private cloud ?

→ All new AWS accounts have a default VPC

→ New EC2 instances are launched into the default VPC if no subnet is specified 

→ Default VPC has comes with internet connectivity by default so ANY EC2 launched can connect to WWW + have a public IPv4 address 

→ EC2 instances in the Default VPC get a public & private IPv4 DNS name 


