VPC - Subnets for IPv4 ? 

Subnets are the small networks within your VPC  

Can be public / private -> depending if they have access to the internet  

Each VPC divided into multiple subnets -> allows you to segment your resources across different AZ’s = better redundancy + availability 

→ AWS reserves 5 IP addresses for each subnet - not available for you to use by your resources ( EC2 instance )

Example 1: 
CIDR block 10.0.0.0/24  = 24 bits are for the network and the 8 rest are for the host range 
32-24 ‎ = 8    so 2 * 8 = 256 IP addresses

Subnet reserves first 4 and last one so :
10.0.0.0 - network address 
10.0.0.1 - reseved for VPC router 
10.0.0.2 - reserved for mapping to amazon provided DNS ( IP address for DNS server )
10.0.0.3 - reserved for future use 
Last one 
10.0.0.255 - Network Broadcaster Address → AWS doesn’t support broadcast in a VPC so address is then reserved 



Internet Gateway and what it is in VCS ?

→ IG allows your resource ( EC2 instance ) within your VPC that has an IP address to connect to the internet 
→ Scaled horizontally ( can handle increase in traffic ) + highly available and redundant 
→Must be created  separately  from a VPC ( not made automatically )

→ can only connect one Internet Gateway to a VPC 
→ Internet Gateways alone do not allow internet access ( you have to update your route tables )
→ Route tables must be updated 


